T1  - Role Perceptions, Satisfaction and Performance Moderated by Organization Level and Participation in Decision Making
AU  - Schuler, Randall S.
Y1  - 1977/03/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255471
DO  - 10.5465/255471
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 159
EP  - 165
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a study which looked at the relationships between role perception and employee satisfaction and performance. Participation in decision making was more effective when there were higher levels of role conflict than lower levels of role conflict. The same pattern held true for role ambiguity. Role ambiguity and participation and role conflict and participation did significantly interact at lower levels of an organization. Overall role conflict was a more important variable than role ambiguity.
AB  - The article discusses a study which looked at the relationships between role perception and employee satisfaction and performance. Participation in decision making was more effective when there were higher levels of role conflict than lower levels of role conflict. The same pattern held true for role ambiguity. Role ambiguity and participation and role conflict and participation did significantly interact at lower levels of an organization. Overall role conflict was a more important variable than role ambiguity.
