TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Comparison of Within- and Across-Subject Analysis of the Expectancy-Valence Model For Predicting Effort
AU  - Muchinsky, Paul M.
Y1  - 1977/03/01
PY  - 1977
DA  - 1977/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255470
DO  - 10.5465/255470
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 154
EP  - 158
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses a study which compared the validity of within and across subjects analyses in predicting job effort. The validity coefficients of the complete model and components varied greatly both within and between individual subjects. The best predictor of self-report effort was a single component of the model. Analysts say the weakest part of the study is that the criterion is not a behavioral measure. The valences, instrumentalities, and expectancies are related to the criterion of a self-report rating of effort.
AB  - The article discusses a study which compared the validity of within and across subjects analyses in predicting job effort. The validity coefficients of the complete model and components varied greatly both within and between individual subjects. The best predictor of self-report effort was a single component of the model. Analysts say the weakest part of the study is that the criterion is not a behavioral measure. The valences, instrumentalities, and expectancies are related to the criterion of a self-report rating of effort.
